    <header>
        <h1>Long-Term Investment Terms</h1>
    </header>

    <main>
        <h2>Asset Allocation</h2>
        <p>Asset allocation is the strategic distribution of investments among various asset classes, such as stocks, bonds, and real estate, to optimize returns while managing risk. A well-balanced asset allocation can help investors achieve their long-term financial goals by spreading risk and capturing potential opportunities in different market conditions.</p>

        <h2>Diversification</h2>
        <p>Diversification is the practice of spreading investments across different types of assets within each asset class to reduce the impact of a poor-performing investment on the overall portfolio. It aims to minimize risk by not putting all eggs in one basket and instead creating a well-rounded and resilient investment mix.</p>

        <h2>Compound Interest</h2>
        <p>Compound interest is the process of earning interest on both the initial principal amount and any previously earned interest. Over time, this compounding effect can significantly boost the growth of investments. It is a fundamental concept for long-term investors looking to maximize their returns.</p>

        <h2>Risk Tolerance</h2>
        <p>Risk tolerance refers to an investor's ability and willingness to endure fluctuations in the value of their investments. It's a crucial factor in determining an appropriate asset allocation and investment strategy. Investors with a high risk tolerance may be comfortable with more volatile investments, while those with a low risk tolerance may prefer more stable, conservative options.</p>

        <h2>Dividend</h2>
        <p>A dividend is a distribution of a portion of a company's earnings to its shareholders. It is typically paid in cash or additional shares of stock. Dividend-paying stocks can provide investors with a regular income stream, making them attractive for long-term investors seeking both capital appreciation and income.</p>

        <h2>Bull Market</h2>
        <p>A bull market is a prolonged period of rising stock prices and overall optimism in the financial markets. It's characterized by strong investor confidence, increased buying activity, and expectations of sustained economic growth. Bull markets are typically favorable for long-term investors as they can lead to substantial portfolio gains.</p>

        <h2>Bear Market</h2>
        <p>A bear market is a sustained period of declining stock prices, often accompanied by pessimism and economic uncertainty. Bear markets can pose challenges for long-term investors, as the value of their investments may decline. However, they can also present buying opportunities for those looking to acquire assets at lower prices.</p>

        <h2>Portfolio</h2>
        <p>A portfolio refers to the collection of investments held by an individual or institution. It can include a variety of asset classes, such as stocks, bonds, real estate, and cash equivalents. Long-term investors carefully construct and manage their portfolios to align with their financial objectives and risk tolerance.</p>

        <h2>Long-Term Investment</h2>
        <p>A long-term investment involves holding assets for an extended period, typically several years or more, with the expectation of achieving financial goals over time. Long-term investors focus on capital appreciation and often prioritize assets that have the potential to grow significantly in value.</p>

        <h2>Asset Management</h2>
        <p>Asset management refers to the professional management of investment portfolios on behalf of clients or investors. Asset managers make strategic decisions regarding asset allocation, security selection, and risk management to optimize returns and achieve the client's financial goals.</p>

        <h2>Market Volatility</h2>
        <p>Market volatility measures the degree of variation in the price of an asset or the overall market over time. Volatile markets can experience rapid price fluctuations, both up and down, which may impact the value of long-term investments. Understanding and managing volatility is important for long-term investors to stay committed to their financial goals.</p>

        <h2>Yield</h2>
        <p>Yield represents the income return generated by an investment and is typically expressed as a percentage. It can be derived from various sources, such as dividends from stocks or interest payments from bonds. Long-term investors often consider yield when evaluating the potential income generated by their investments.</p>

        <h2>Capital Gains</h2>
        <p>Capital gains are profits earned from the sale of an investment, such as stocks or real estate. Long-term capital gains, generated from assets held for over one year, often receive preferential tax treatment. Long-term investors may strategically manage their investments to minimize capital gains taxes.</p>

        <h2>Tax-Deferred Growth</h2>
        <p>Tax-deferred growth refers to the accumulation of investment earnings without immediate taxation. Many retirement accounts, such as 401(k)s and IRAs, offer tax-deferred growth, allowing investors to potentially grow their assets more efficiently over the long term.</p>

        <h2>Risk-Adjusted Return</h2>
        <p>Risk-adjusted return assesses an investment's performance relative to its level of risk. It helps investors evaluate whether the returns generated are adequate compensation for the risks taken. Long-term investors seek investments that provide favorable risk-adjusted returns.</p>

        <h2>Exit Strategy</h2>
        <p>An exit strategy outlines how and when an investor intends to sell or liquidate their investments. It's an essential consideration for long-term investors as it helps ensure that financial goals are met and that investments are managed effectively.</p>
    </main>
